    "answer": "c",
    "explanation": "• PSA—glycoprotein which is a serine protease. <br>• Normal upper limit—4 nmol/mL. <br>• Serum PSA level is the most sensitive test for early detection of <br>prostatic cancer and is elevated in approximately 65% of cases. <br>• Man with locally confined prostate cancer—<10 to 15 nmol/mL. <br>• Man with metastatic prostate cancer—>30 nmol/mL. PSA falls to low <br>levels after successful androgen ablation. PSA is a reliable marker for <br>the progress of advanced disease. • PSA—glycoprotein which is a serine protease.  • Normal upper limit—4 nmol/mL.  • Serum PSA level is the most sensitive test for early detection of  prostatic cancer and is elevated in approximately 65% of cases.  • Man with locally confined prostate cancer—<10 to 15 nmol/mL.  • Man with metastatic prostate cancer—>30 nmol/mL. PSA falls to low  levels after successful androgen ablation. PSA is a reliable marker for  the progress of advanced disease.",
