    "explanation": "• Osler's nodes—hard, painful, tender, subcutaneous swelling in finger, <br>toes, palm, and soles seen in infective endocarditis. <br>• Subcutaneous nodules are painless, pea-sized, hard nodules beneath <br>the skin particularly over tendon, joints, and bony prominence, are <br>major criteria of rheumatic fever. <br>• Erythema nodosum—painful nodules or plaques up to 5 cm, appear in <br>crops. Causes—drugs (sulfonamide, OCP, penicillin, bromide), <br>sarcoidosis (most common), inflammatory bowel disease, streptococci, <br>tuberculosis, leprosy, Yersinia, chlamydia, histoplasmosis, <br>coccidioidomycosis, blastomycosis.",
