    "id": "UPSC_2005_P2_Q39",
    "num": "39",
    "question": "Normocytic normochromic anemia  may be the feature of the following conditions, except",
    "options": {
      "a": "Aplastic anemia",
      "b": "Anemia due to chronic blood loss",
      "c": "Anemia in chronic  kidney diseases",
      "d": "Anemia due to chronic infections"
    },
    "answer": "b",
    "explanation": "Morphologic <br>classification of anemia • Microcytic hypochromic: MCV, MCH, MCHC—all <br>reduced. Causes: 1. Iron-deficiency anemia (a. During infancy—nutritional, <br>posthemorrhagic, b. Older child—posthemorrhagic, nutritional), 2. Ineffective <br>erythropoiesis—thalassemia, pyridoxine responsive anemia, lead poisoning, <br>dyserythropoietic anemia. • Normocytic, normochromic: MCV, MCH, MCHC—<br>all normal. Causes: 1. Acute blood loss, 2. Hemolysis (reticulocyte count high), <br>3. Impaired cell production (reticulocyte count low) - a. Normal leucocyte and <br>platelet: physiological anemia of infancy, infections, pure red cell aplasia. b. <br>Normal or decreased leucocyte and platelets: chronic renal and liver disease, <br>hypothyroidism. c. Reduced leucocyte and platelet: aplastic anemia, leukemia. <br>• Macrocytic: MCV—raised. Causes: 1. Megaloblastic erythropoiesis - a. <br>Nutritional—vitamin B12 deficiency, folate deficiency, Kwashiorkor. b. Drugs—<br>methotrexate, phenytoin. 2. Nonmegaloblastic erythropoiesis—chronic <br>hemolytic anemia, liver disease, hypothyroidism, Diamond–Blackfan syndrome. <br>Malabsorption.",
    "year": "2005",
    "paper": "2",
    "tags": [
      "Surgery"
    ]
