    "id": "UPSC_2005_P2_Q88",
    "num": "88",
    "question": "A pregnant woman with mitral stenosis with grade II dyspnea at 38  weeks comes to the antenatal clinic. The appropriate management in this  case would be",
    "options": {
      "a": "Induction of labor immediately to avoid further cardiac load",
      "b": "Outpatient management with tablets digoxin and Lasix till she goes in labor",
      "c": "Admission of the patient to achieve the maximum functional capacity of the  heart",
      "d": "Perform immediate cesarean section to avoid further cardiac load and  deterioration"
    },
    "answer": "c",
    "explanation": "Admission of patient with heart disease in <br>pregnancy <br>1. Elective a. Grade I—at least 2 weeks prior to EDD. b. Grade II—at 28th <br>week, especially, in case of unfavorable social surroundings. c. Grades III <br>and IV—as soon as pregnancy is diagnosed and kept in hospital <br>throughout pregnancy. <br>2. Emergency a. Deterioration of functional grading. b. Appearance of <br>dyspnea or cough or basal crepitations or tachyarrhythmia. c. <br>Appearance of any pregnancy complication like anemia, pre-eclampsia. <br>Place of cesarean section: In general, there is no indication of cesarean <br>section for heart disease. Cesarean section is mainly done for obstetric <br>indications and in coarctation of aorta. Reference: Dutta, Textbook of <br>Obstetrics, 7th Ed., Pg. 278.",
    "year": "2005",
    "paper": "2",
    "tags": [
      "PSM"
    ]
